From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0032/N] os_bsd_aarch64: csp/c29 for SPELL_REG_SP/FP under purecap

`os::current_stack_pointer()` does:

  void *sp;
  __asm__("mov %0, " SPELL_REG_SP : "=r"(sp));

With `SPELL_REG_SP "sp"` the generated assembly is `mov c?, sp`
on Morello purecap (where `%0` is constrained to a capability
register, since `sp` is `void *` = `__intcap`). The Morello
assembler rejects this — the legacy `sp` name refers to the
integer view of the stack pointer and is not a valid source for
a capability-typed destination. The capability stack pointer is
spelled `csp`.

Define `SPELL_REG_SP` to `csp` and `SPELL_REG_FP` to `c29` under
`__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__`. The latter follows Morello calling
convention (c29 is the capability frame pointer; there is no
formal `cfp` alias).

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md §6 (patch 0032)

--- a/src/hotspot/os_cpu/bsd_aarch64/os_bsd_aarch64.cpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/os_cpu/bsd_aarch64/os_bsd_aarch64.cpp
@@ -81,8 +81,15 @@
 # include <pthread_np.h>
 #endif

+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+// Morello purecap: stack pointer is the capability register csp; legacy 'sp'
+// names the integer view and is not a valid mov source for a cap-typed dest.
+#define SPELL_REG_SP "csp"
+#define SPELL_REG_FP "c29"
+#else
 #define SPELL_REG_SP "sp"
 #define SPELL_REG_FP "fp"
+#endif

 #ifdef __APPLE__
 // see darwin-xnu/osfmk/mach/arm/_structs.h
